Introduction

Milliman PRM Analytics is a predictive analytics solution capable of predicting any number of healthcare management risks. The primary predictive analytics are the Opportunity Prospective Scores.

Milliman PRM Analytics is not a standalone solution. It can also be integrated with an existing care management system for comprehensive care management. The PRM Care Coordinator Reports provide care managers with a comprehensive view of recent patient clinical and claims activity, making management more efficient and effective.

Milliman PRM Analytics are backed by more than 65 years of experience in healthcare consulting, data analytics, operational analysis and problem solving. The solutions offered by this tool leverage a unique reporting structure and custom analytics that help meet coming healthcare challenges head on.

This user guide is designed to give users an understanding of the latest features of the PRM Client Administration Console and step by step instructions for using the system.

Please note that these instructions are ONLY meant for client users who have been granted access.

Note: Access to various functionality is dictated by what was enabled for the role assigned to the user and the options enabled for the client. For illustration purposes, all of the functionality is enabled in the screen shots shown below.

PRM Client Administrator Console

Overview

Millframe 4.1.0 is an application that allows the Milliman administrators to add and manage users, and set different roles for the users. It allows the Client Administrators to add and manage users, and set data restrictions for them. The Client users can view the Qlikview reports using Web Portal interface. The application also allows the Client Publisher to publish the contents for a Client. The application Millframe consists of five modules. The PRM Web Portal module allows the client users to view the reports for the group(s) they are associated with.

Definitions

Group – a container used to associate users to reports (QVW). A group may contain any number of users and reports. Note: as a best practice a group should contain exactly 1 report and multiple users; however, this is not enforced programmatically.

Specific interfaces will not function if associated with a group that contains multiple reports. There interfaces include

  • Client administrator console (CAC)

  • Client publishing console (CPC)

Both web interfaces could result in personal health information (PHI) leaking due to ambiguous situations if a group containing multiple reports was allowed to be loaded. As a result, both web interfaces actively check to ensure groups contain only one report. One report and multiple users is considered to be a best practice.

QVW – A document created by QlikView, BI analysis application; stores a QlikView application, which contains reports, charts, and KPI; used for analyzing data. QVX: QlikView data exchange is a new file/stream format for high performance data input into QlikView. Referred to as a Report.

Super Group - A collection of groups. The only groups shown in the Super Group console are groups that only contain 1 QVW.

Client Publisher – Console created to allow an authorized person to push updated content to the production server.

Updated Content - Content that already exists on production, but is being refreshed with a new data set. Note: the creation of New Content on the production server requires the involvement of Indianapolis administrators.

Getting Started

A prerequisite for being able to use the Client Administrator Console is for the PRM administrator to look at the user’s profile and to make sure that the Client User Administrator box has been checked.

In this case the box has been checked. So next the Client Administrator logs in to the Web Portal.

  1. After logging in, the Client Administrator clicks on a specific report from the drop-down menu. For this demo, we will use the New York group report.

    Note: Only Milliman administrators see a filter box. Client administrator will only have access to their specific reports.

  1. This is a list of all the Client-user Administrators for the New York group.

  1. The left hand side displays the users also displays their status as client administrators.

  2. On the right side of the administrator display page is the data restriction tree. This is where you restrict users’ access to the data.

  1. As an example we will select one of the Active administrators.

  1. When you select a user, the Restriction Tree is highlighted. Expanding the tree reveals the access that the client administrator has to different Providers within the Group. All this information is coming from the QlikView report.

  1. Clicking on a different client administrator show the access that they have to different practices.

  1. When you want to give or restrict access to data, you check or uncheck the boxes of groups you wish to allow or deny access to.

  1. When you are finished making your selections, click the Apply Changes button.

  1. The modification to the access takes place. As a shared server it may take a few moments.

  1. When complete, a notification message appears.

  1. So When BA Martin clicks on the Report icon in the Web Portal, they will now have access to the information of both Arlington Orthopedics and Clayton R. Perry.

  1. Now we will discuss the User view. You will notice that some of the users have little Superman icons to the left of their names. These are Super Users.

    No one actually sees these icons but Indianapolis personnel.

  1. When you click on a user’s status, a dialog box appears that tells an administrator the last time the user accessed the system.

  1. Clicking on other users, different messages appear. Below is a test user message.

  1. The No Welcome status means that the user was not sent a welcome message with instructions on how to access the PRM system. Sometimes the user prefers a customized email on access rather than a generic welcome email.

  1. Another user status is Password Reset. This means either the User Administrator has reset the password or the User could have clicked the Reset Password button on the portal and reset their password.

  1. There is also a Notes box, where the Client Administrator can add notes; however this may go away in future PRM releases.

Client Administrator Toolbar

  1. The Delete button allows the Client Administrator to delete a User.

  1. Deleting a user doesn’t mean that you have deleted their account from the system. It means that you have removed their access to this report. They may still have access to other reports. If this is the only report that they have access to, then it will delete their account.

  2. Suspend/(Un)suspend will take the user to another area of the report.

  1. When you refresh the screen, it shows that the user’s account has been suspended. When the user’s account has been suspended that are unable to log in to the Web Portal.

  1. Reset Password. Clicking on this button will send the User and email telling them to reset their password.

  1. Before sending the email, a confirmation box will ask if you want to send the email.

  1. Email All builds a list for the administrator to send out a group email. Note: Sometimes the group list is so long that it exceeds the email limit of the email client. So there is a possibility that some users may not receive the blanket email.

26. Email is used to email an individual user.

27. Add User.

  1. When you click on this button it takes you to a new screen.

  1. This gives you a Restriction Tree and a drop down where you can add a new user.

  1. After adding the user in the box, you click Save.

  1. Before hitting Save, you must make Data Restrictions Selections from the list.

  1. After saving, the site sends a confirmation message.

  1. When you go and look at the individual record to confirm the user addition and data restriction, the status appears as Password Reset.

  1. The reason for this is, that the first time a new user logs in, they have to change their password via the Send Welcome email they receive with a secure link.

Example Send Welcome email.

  1. As an alternative for clients who prefer a manual email reset, you may place a bracket within the account name before hitting Save and uncheck the Send Welcome box.

  1. This will add the user to the system and then you can send them a manual email with their bracketed password.

  1. Using the + buttons at the bottom left, you can add multiple users.

  1. Note: If you accidentally add a name for an existing account, it will just add any new information to the existing account and not create a second record.

  2. This dialog box appears after action to allow the user to refresh their browser.

  1. In the case where a manual email is sent to the user and they log in without the link in the Welcome email, they will receive this prompt the first time they log in.

  1. At this point, they will change their password and answer a Security Question as part of the Password Recovery Settings.
